        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Louisville Ky</placeName>, <date>May 8th
                1854</date></p>
            <p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>, Editor of the Occident</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Herewith you will receive advertisement,<lb/> which please insert in
                your periodical once, /provided it will ap<lb/>pear in your <date>June</date>
                number:/, and forward account to me for ad<lb/> justment. Should any
                    <sic>enquiry</sic> be made of you, I am authorized to say<lb/> that the salary
                will be the least about 600 Dollars p. a. and<lb/> that a good practical English
                Scholar only can obtain the<lb/> situation.</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Respectfully yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">By order of the Directory</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)"><persName role="author">B H. Gotthelf</persName> Secretary</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Teacher wanted.</p>
            <p>The congregational School about to be established in K. K. Adas Israel in
                    <placeName>Louisville Ky</placeName> is desirous of procuring the services<lb/>
                of a practical English Scholar capable of imparting instruction<lb/> in the Hebrew
                language and Religion. A liberal salary<lb/> will be given and Testimonials of
                character and qualifications<lb/> required. To <add>?</add> further particulars
                address</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)"><persName>H. Uberdorfer</persName> Pres.of the Board of
                <lb/>Directors</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">or <persName role="author">Revd. B. H. Gotthelf</persName> Sec.</p>
            <p>P. S. I will communicate to you in a few day'<sic>s</sic> my success <del>of
                a</del><lb/> in distributing your bibles—and other particulars concerning the<lb/>
                congregational affairs; which are very encouraging. I have</p>
            <p rend="The following is written at the bottom of the page.">#</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>sold 19 copies, but as yet not received one single Dollar<lb/> for it.— I Hope you
                will <sic>safe</sic> a little space for me<lb/> in your next Occident.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Send the Occident for <date>April</date> &amp; <date>May</date>
                To</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)"><persName>Marcus Straus</persName> in
                        <placeName><sic>Lesxington</sic> Ky</placeName>, and continue<lb/> to send
                the same regularly. If you prefer it, you<lb/> may address them to me, and <hi
                    rend="underline">I</hi> will send them, as<lb/> it may be perhaps<del>s</del>
                the safest way.—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">To <sic>morrow</sic> evening will be a congreg. meeting, the
                result<lb/> of which will be the principal<del>e</del> tendency of my
                    <add>next</add> communi<lb/>cation.</p>
            <p rend="Note:">Scribbled line next to “congreg” in the text above.</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">Truly &amp; most respectfully yours—</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)"><persName role="author">B H Gotthelf</persName>.</p>
            <p>————</p>
            <p>Should you know of any good Teacher, such as we want,<lb/> I wish you would let me
                know privately— For a good<lb/> Teacher the situation would soon become a permanent
                one<lb/> and the congregation would willingly pay seven or eight<lb/> Hundred
                Dollars after the first year.—Answer as soon<lb/> as convenient.—</p>
            <p rend="The following is written at the bottom left.">20-238</p>
